1
00:01:27,480 --> 00:01:30,295
I ask you now to pronounce judgment...

2
00:01:30,456 --> 00:01:31,917
...on those accused.

3
00:01:34,295 --> 00:01:35,540
On this...

4
00:01:35,704 --> 00:01:39,696
This mindless aberration,
whose only means of expression...

5
00:01:39,862 --> 00:01:42,132
...are wanton violence and destruction.

6
00:01:43,350 --> 00:01:44,560
On the woman, Ursa...

7
00:01:45,014 --> 00:01:48,113
...whose perversions
and unreasoning hatred of all mankind...

8
00:01:48,599 --> 00:01:52,014
...have threatened even the children
of the planet Krypton.

9
00:01:53,174 --> 00:01:55,793
Finally, General Zod.

10
00:01:55,959 --> 00:01:58,097
Chief architect
of this intended revolution...

11
00:01:58,262 --> 00:02:03,117
...and author of this insidious plot
to establish a new order amongst us...

12
00:02:03,478 --> 00:02:06,861
...with himself as absolute ruler.

13
00:02:07,798 --> 00:02:10,132
The decision of the council
will now be heard.

14
00:02:10,293 --> 00:02:11,538
<i>Guilty.</i>

15
00:02:12,502 --> 00:02:13,647
<i>- Guilty.
- Guilty.</i>

16
00:02:15,542 --> 00:02:17,069
<i>Guilty.</i>

17
00:02:19,319 --> 00:02:21,140
The vote must be unanimous, Jor-El.

18
00:02:22,102 --> 00:02:24,436
It has therefore
now become your decision.

19
00:02:24,598 --> 00:02:26,835
You alone will condemn us if you wish...

20
00:02:26,999 --> 00:02:29,813
...and you alone
will be held responsible by me.

21
00:02:39,957 --> 00:02:42,324
You will bow down before me, Jor-El.

22
00:02:42,485 --> 00:02:43,630
I swear it.

23
00:02:43,797 --> 00:02:48,586
No matter that it takes an eternity,
you will bow down before me!

24
00:02:48,757 --> 00:02:49,804
Both you...

25
00:02:50,069 --> 00:02:51,116
...and then one day...

26
00:02:51,285 --> 00:02:53,107
...your heirs!

27
00:03:21,299 --> 00:03:24,715
You will bow down before me!

28
00:03:26,611 --> 00:03:28,881
- Forgive me!
- I'll be back!

29
00:03:29,043 --> 00:03:30,122
Forgive me!

30
00:04:01,842 --> 00:04:06,152
<i>Your mother Lara has sent you
three blankets, of red, yellow and blue.</i>

31
00:04:07,538 --> 00:04:09,840
<i>Their protection
will ensure your strength.</i>

32
00:05:16,592 --> 00:05:20,366
It's kryptonite, Superman.
A little souvenir from the old hometown.

33
00:05:25,327 --> 00:05:29,702
You were great in your day, Superman.
But it just stands to reason...

34
00:05:29,871 --> 00:05:32,206
...when it came time
to cash in your chips...

35
00:05:32,368 --> 00:05:35,662
...this old, diseased maniac...

36
00:05:35,822 --> 00:05:37,678
...would be your banker.

37
00:05:40,974 --> 00:05:42,830
Mind over muscle.

38
00:06:15,214 --> 00:06:17,318
Why did you kiss me first?

39
00:06:18,542 --> 00:06:21,443
It... I didn't think you'd let me later.

40
00:06:21,613 --> 00:06:23,337
Stand aside, now.

41
00:07:56,521 --> 00:07:58,463
Free!

42
00:11:33,859 --> 00:11:37,633
Nice fresh melons.
Nice fresh melons. Get them fresh here.

43
00:11:37,794 --> 00:11:40,543
Good for the cooking, huh?
Look at this, the best.

44
00:11:42,242 --> 00:11:44,663
"Lex Luthor's scheme bombs.
Superman saves nation.

45
00:11:44,834 --> 00:11:48,130
Master criminal draws harsh sentence.
Exclusive story by Lois Lane.

46
00:11:48,290 --> 00:11:50,329
Photographs by James Olsen."

47
00:11:50,498 --> 00:11:53,564
Luthor, you never looked lovelier.

48
00:11:53,730 --> 00:11:54,842
Lois, terrific job.

49
00:11:55,009 --> 00:11:56,896
- Thanks, chief.
- Great story, really great.

50
00:11:57,057 --> 00:11:59,163
Hey, good morning, chief. You're late.

51
00:11:59,330 --> 00:12:02,111
Yeah, Miss Lane, that's a great story.
One of the best.

52
00:12:02,272 --> 00:12:06,429
Well, Jimmy, usually a picture isn't worth
a thousand words when I write the story...

53
00:12:06,593 --> 00:12:08,349
...but in this case, congratulations.

54
00:12:08,513 --> 00:12:09,822
- Yeah, thanks a lot.
- Yeah.

55
00:12:10,849 --> 00:12:14,144
There's Mr. Kent. Bet he wishes
he'd been around when it all happened.

56
00:12:14,304 --> 00:12:16,725
Clark, he's never around
when Superman appears.

57
00:12:16,896 --> 00:12:18,326
Poor guy.

58
00:12:27,135 --> 00:12:28,696
- You got a page in the front?
- Yeah.

59
00:12:31,679 --> 00:12:33,916
Miss Lane got the best story.

60
00:12:40,992 --> 00:12:42,846
Good morning, Lois.

61
00:12:44,160 --> 00:12:45,404
Hi.

62
00:13:21,342 --> 00:13:23,545
Lane, Kent, get in here!

63
00:13:23,710 --> 00:13:25,467
Now, see, Jimmy,
you got me in trouble.

64
00:13:25,631 --> 00:13:28,664
- We were talking.
- So long. A big mistake.

65
00:13:29,470 --> 00:13:31,707
Next time, don't do that to me.

66
00:13:32,030 --> 00:13:35,510
- Good morning, Lois. How are you today?
- Oh, I'm just super. Thanks.

67
00:13:35,678 --> 00:13:37,271
- Good morning, Mr. White.
- I'm super.

68
00:13:37,438 --> 00:13:40,667
- Yeah, morning. You're late, Kent.
- I know. I'm sorry, Mr. White.

69
00:13:40,830 --> 00:13:43,001
- I got stuck in traffic.
- Oh, that's a new one.

70
00:13:43,166 --> 00:13:44,856
- Excuse me?
- I mean, as opposed to:

71
00:13:45,021 --> 00:13:48,337
"I was stuck in a phone booth" or
"I got locked into the men's bathroom."

72
00:13:48,509 --> 00:13:51,030
Lois, what are you talking about?
I'm sorry I was late.

73
00:13:51,198 --> 00:13:53,848
If you two wanna bicker,
I have just the assignment for you.

74
00:13:54,013 --> 00:13:57,842
You're gonna pose as a honeymoon couple
to get an exposé on the newlywed racket.

75
00:13:58,013 --> 00:14:01,559
Some of those hotels are bilking
those poor kids for every cent they can get.

76
00:14:01,725 --> 00:14:04,822
Real human-interest stuff.
Make your Aunt Hattie cry her eyes out.

77
00:14:05,084 --> 00:14:07,987
- Newlyweds?
- That is a great idea, Mr. White.

78
00:14:08,156 --> 00:14:11,638
- I'm sorry, but I'm in the middle of a series...
- I mean, it wouldn't take long.

79
00:14:11,806 --> 00:14:16,114
We could just fly right up there
and zoom back down again.

80
00:14:16,285 --> 00:14:18,456
No, Superman?

81
00:14:18,621 --> 00:14:21,687
Yeah. If he'd give you two a ride,
maybe we could save a couple bucks.

82
00:14:21,949 --> 00:14:24,217
I gotta see young Olsen.
Six lousy photographs...

83
00:14:24,380 --> 00:14:28,636
...and that kid's hitting me up for a raise.
- Excuse me. Mr. White? Could we talk?

84
00:14:28,796 --> 00:14:30,257
Darn.

85
00:14:31,164 --> 00:14:33,947
You look like the cat who swallowed
the canary this morning.

86
00:14:34,108 --> 00:14:37,785
A canary? No, actually I was
thinking of something bigger...

87
00:14:37,948 --> 00:14:40,794
...something that flies,
something more in blue.

88
00:14:41,243 --> 00:14:43,131
Lois, as usual, I'm totally in the dark...

89
00:14:43,292 --> 00:14:46,390
Let me just turn on the lights
for you then.

90
00:14:48,220 --> 00:14:49,910
Get the picture?

91
00:14:51,738 --> 00:14:55,186
I didn't put this together until
this morning. Which is really strange...

92
00:14:55,355 --> 00:14:58,519
...because a good reporter isn't supposed to
let anything slip by her.

93
00:14:58,683 --> 00:15:01,017
Well, that's very amusing. Yes.

94
00:15:01,178 --> 00:15:02,586
- Excuse me.
- Amusing?

95
00:15:02,747 --> 00:15:06,968
- Yes, sirree, that's... That's very amusing.
- Amusing, huh?

96
00:15:07,194 --> 00:15:11,122
Tall, broad shoulders...

97
00:15:11,514 --> 00:15:13,457
...dark hair.

98
00:15:13,626 --> 00:15:16,440
Gotta give you credit,
you really had me fooled.

99
00:15:16,601 --> 00:15:19,090
And I'm nobody's fool...

100
00:15:19,866 --> 00:15:21,524
...Superman.

101
00:15:21,978 --> 00:15:23,255
Superman?

102
00:15:23,418 --> 00:15:27,410
You mean you think I'm Superman?

103
00:15:28,025 --> 00:15:31,025
- Willing to bet my life on it.
- Lois, you know, you are priceless.

104
00:15:31,193 --> 00:15:34,063
Really. That is the single most
ridiculous thing I've ever...

105
00:15:35,417 --> 00:15:38,166
- Lois, what are you doing?
- You wouldn't let me die, Superman.

106
00:16:16,505 --> 00:16:20,018
- Oh, God.
- Help her out. Help her out.

107
00:16:20,408 --> 00:16:23,091
- Clark!
- Lois, what have you done?

108
00:16:23,480 --> 00:16:26,001
Clark, the... You're not...

109
00:16:28,503 --> 00:16:31,700
Hey, Clark, you seen Lois?

110
00:16:34,519 --> 00:16:36,243
She just stepped out for a minute.

111
00:16:52,950 --> 00:16:55,820
This is how it ends for
the greatest criminal mind of our time.

112
00:16:55,991 --> 00:16:58,161
Not with a whimper, not with a bang.

113
00:16:58,326 --> 00:17:00,747
How do they choose
to reward Lex Luthor...

114
00:17:00,919 --> 00:17:02,773
...the greatest genius in this world?

115
00:17:02,934 --> 00:17:06,677
Do they give him glory or treasure?
What, matter of fact, do they give him?

116
00:17:06,838 --> 00:17:10,766
Life plus 25, Luthor. Get to work.

117
00:17:14,902 --> 00:17:17,423
Don't feel bad, Mr. Luthor.
It almost worked.

118
00:17:17,591 --> 00:17:20,307
I mean, California almost
fell down, right in the ocean.

119
00:17:20,470 --> 00:17:22,194
Millions of people was almost killed.

120
00:17:22,358 --> 00:17:25,423
If it hadn't been for that guy
Superman, that overgrown Boy Scout.

121
00:17:25,589 --> 00:17:28,688
- I want my Liberace record back tonight.
- Tonight?

122
00:17:28,854 --> 00:17:33,710
What are you gonna do with a guy like that?
He flies around so fast and everything.

123
00:17:34,677 --> 00:17:37,743
I mean, they can't even trace
that guy on that radar they got.

124
00:17:37,942 --> 00:17:40,756
Every time they try, he just flies off.

125
00:17:40,917 --> 00:17:42,227
- Where?
- North.

126
00:17:42,421 --> 00:17:44,144
Why?

127
00:17:44,309 --> 00:17:45,553
To ski?

128
00:17:45,717 --> 00:17:48,979
Otis, every man has his vulnerable point.

129
00:17:49,141 --> 00:17:52,240
Some, like you, Otis,
have more than one.

130
00:17:52,406 --> 00:17:54,260
I didn't see Superman's in time.

131
00:17:54,421 --> 00:17:57,902
But now, through patience,
invention, and skill...

132
00:17:58,901 --> 00:18:01,867
...my little black box
is just about ready.

133
00:18:02,036 --> 00:18:05,135
Oh, that little black box in our cell?

134
00:18:08,020 --> 00:18:10,954
That little black box, Mr. Luthor...

135
00:18:12,435 --> 00:18:14,258
...what's it for?

136
00:18:14,420 --> 00:18:19,984
That little black box goes beyond
any normal, conventional radar.

137
00:18:20,147 --> 00:18:22,699
It tracks alpha waves.

138
00:18:25,107 --> 00:18:27,659
Alpha waves. Yeah.

139
00:18:27,826 --> 00:18:30,445
<i>I could've said it tracked pasta e fagioli,
couldn't I?</i>

140
00:18:30,611 --> 00:18:34,091
Oh, with garlic, Mr. Luthor. And butter.

141
00:18:34,259 --> 00:18:35,600
Boy.

142
00:18:38,643 --> 00:18:43,978
Those alpha waves will
take me north to his secret.

143
00:18:44,147 --> 00:18:48,685
And when I have his secret,
I'll have Superman.

144
00:18:51,443 --> 00:18:54,094
Slasher Fogelstein's a bed wetter.

145
00:18:58,546 --> 00:19:02,321
Slasher Fogelstein's a bed wetter.
Pass it.

146
00:19:07,570 --> 00:19:09,426
Hi, Mr. Fogelstein.

147
00:19:09,874 --> 00:19:12,295
- too fast. Can you get the speed right?

148
00:19:12,466 --> 00:19:15,281
I told you, they installed those
three weeks ago.

149
00:19:16,177 --> 00:19:17,126
Hey.

150
00:19:18,001 --> 00:19:22,027
You follow the bouncing ball for a while.
Thing's giving me a headache.

151
00:19:22,193 --> 00:19:25,161
Anyway, somebody's
gotta check up on those guys.

152
00:19:25,329 --> 00:19:28,046
Yeah, I keep on forgetting about them.

153
00:19:28,209 --> 00:19:30,860
How long they been up there, 45 days?

154
00:19:31,026 --> 00:19:33,840
The whole world's forgotten about it.

155
00:19:35,985 --> 00:19:38,057
<i>Houston calling Artemis II.</i>

156
00:19:38,832 --> 00:19:41,550
<i>Houston calling Artemis II. Come in.</i>

157
00:19:41,713 --> 00:19:44,167
<i>Morning, Houston. Hold on, Nate.</i>

158
00:19:44,336 --> 00:19:46,191
<i>- Yo.
- How are things going?</i>

159
00:19:46,929 --> 00:19:49,295
All systems normal, Houston.

160
00:19:49,456 --> 00:19:52,239
Andy is out doing the geological survey.

161
00:19:52,401 --> 00:19:54,604
<i>More rocks. Nice.</i>

162
00:19:54,768 --> 00:19:57,736
And cosmonaut Boris
is getting some soil samples.

163
00:19:57,904 --> 00:20:00,359
By the way, Boris and I are engaged.

164
00:20:00,848 --> 00:20:03,847
I had a feeling about you guys
when I saw your Rorschach tests.

165
00:20:04,016 --> 00:20:06,220
Just a little détente
humor there, Houston.

166
00:20:06,384 --> 00:20:08,293
<i>Surface conditions unchanged?</i>

167
00:20:08,464 --> 00:20:11,367
Well, it's mighty
pretty out there. Mighty...

168
00:20:13,424 --> 00:20:15,398
<i>...pretty.
- Mighty pretty.</i>

169
00:20:15,599 --> 00:20:17,640
<i>Right.</i>

170
00:20:18,000 --> 00:20:19,788
<i>Look, Nate?</i>

171
00:20:19,951 --> 00:20:21,479
<i>Nate, wake up, will you?</i>

172
00:20:21,648 --> 00:20:24,103
That's it. I'm dreaming.

173
00:20:24,272 --> 00:20:26,443
<i>Artemis, come in.</i>

174
00:20:26,640 --> 00:20:30,534
Well, Houston, we seem to have
an unidentified flying object.

175
00:20:30,703 --> 00:20:32,045
Unidentified?

176
00:20:32,687 --> 00:20:35,207
<i>- What does it look like?
- Well...</i>

177
00:20:35,375 --> 00:20:37,961
...a lot like a girl.

178
00:20:58,414 --> 00:21:00,137
You.

179
00:21:00,846 --> 00:21:04,195
- What kind of a creature are you?
- Just a man.

180
00:21:04,942 --> 00:21:06,949
A man?

181
00:22:01,389 --> 00:22:04,006
What a fragile sort of life form this is.

182
00:22:28,330 --> 00:22:30,884
Houston, come in. Come in, Houston.

183
00:22:39,050 --> 00:22:40,392
Come in, Houston. Come in.

184
00:22:40,554 --> 00:22:42,114
Attempting manual liftoff.

185
00:22:42,315 --> 00:22:43,492
Can somebody hear me?

186
00:22:43,946 --> 00:22:45,702
Houston!

187
00:22:46,666 --> 00:22:47,745
Come on.

188
00:22:50,506 --> 00:22:52,229
Come on, Houston!

189
00:22:53,066 --> 00:22:55,400
Oh, no. No!

190
00:22:55,914 --> 00:22:57,702
Somebody help me!

191
00:23:04,009 --> 00:23:06,879
<i>- Artemis, Houston calling. Come in.
- What's going on?</i>

192
00:23:07,049 --> 00:23:10,345
- I don't know. We've lost contact.
- So?

193
00:23:10,506 --> 00:23:12,132
Well, we really...

194
00:23:12,714 --> 00:23:14,470
<i>Artemis, come in, please.</i>

195
00:23:16,714 --> 00:23:20,259
All right, which one of you guys
is using the hair dryer?

196
00:23:22,506 --> 00:23:27,142
Strange. I tore those
metal fibers like paper.

197
00:23:27,305 --> 00:23:31,079
And what he did was amazing.

198
00:23:31,240 --> 00:23:35,496
- Something is happening.
- Yes, to all of us.

199
00:23:37,609 --> 00:23:41,634
The closer we come to an
atmosphere with only one sun...

200
00:23:41,800 --> 00:23:43,556
...a yellow sun...

201
00:23:43,720 --> 00:23:47,517
...the more our molecular
density gives us unlimited powers.

202
00:23:47,689 --> 00:23:49,412
They come from there.

203
00:23:49,576 --> 00:23:51,485
A place called Houston.

204
00:23:51,655 --> 00:23:53,958
Then we will go there too...

205
00:23:54,120 --> 00:23:55,974
...to rule.

206
00:23:56,424 --> 00:23:58,977
Finally, to rule.

207
00:24:09,031 --> 00:24:10,689
Three-eighty-two, out.

208
00:24:11,559 --> 00:24:13,828
Three-eighty-three, out.

209
00:24:14,567 --> 00:24:16,738
Three-eighty-four, out.

210
00:24:17,670 --> 00:24:19,874
Three-eighty-five, out.

211
00:24:23,111 --> 00:24:25,347
Lights out, Luthor.

212
00:24:25,894 --> 00:24:28,032
I said, lights out.

213
00:24:30,502 --> 00:24:34,048
You guys are about 10 seconds
away from solitary, you know that?

214
00:24:36,070 --> 00:24:38,011
I told you to...

215
00:24:52,870 --> 00:24:54,943
Freeze, freeze.

216
00:25:26,469 --> 00:25:28,291
Mr. Luthor.

217
00:25:29,572 --> 00:25:31,961
- How we gonna get over that wall?
- How'd we get in?

218
00:25:32,740 --> 00:25:35,195
- We flew in here, remember?
- That's how we'll get out.

219
00:25:35,364 --> 00:25:37,600
Oh, no, not that guy.

220
00:25:41,252 --> 00:25:42,910
Did you just go "psst"?

221
00:25:43,076 --> 00:25:46,110
I wish I had, Mr. Luthor, before we left.

222
00:25:47,684 --> 00:25:49,855
Not that "psst," that "psst."

223
00:25:53,092 --> 00:25:55,775
- Don't go "psst" when I go "psst."
- You do it.

224
00:25:59,139 --> 00:26:01,212
Go out there and find it.

225
00:26:01,891 --> 00:26:06,168
- What am I looking for?
- You'll know when you see it.

226
00:26:16,899 --> 00:26:19,484
I think I found it.

227
00:26:24,451 --> 00:26:26,239
What is it?

228
00:26:27,203 --> 00:26:29,952
It's a ladder, you dummy.

229
00:26:30,690 --> 00:26:32,065
Hi, Miss Teschmacher.

230
00:26:40,674 --> 00:26:41,786
Come on.

231
00:26:42,562 --> 00:26:46,041
Hurry up. Hurry up.

232
00:26:46,594 --> 00:26:48,733
Come on, hurry.

233
00:26:49,697 --> 00:26:51,966
Otis, hold that ladder. Hurry up.

234
00:26:52,129 --> 00:26:55,806
<i>- yard line, touchdown!
Oh, what a beautiful play.</i>

235
00:26:55,969 --> 00:26:58,588
<i>But there's a marker downfield.
It could be against...</i>

236
00:27:03,937 --> 00:27:04,951
- Come up.
- Come on.

237
00:27:05,121 --> 00:27:07,609
Here I come, Mr. Luthor.

238
00:27:09,313 --> 00:27:10,425
- Get off. Get off.
- Otis!

239
00:27:12,161 --> 00:27:14,747
- We're sinking!
- Get off, get off!

240
00:27:31,071 --> 00:27:33,143
Very good,
Miss Teschmacher. Very good.

241
00:27:33,311 --> 00:27:35,897
- What am I doing here? Why am I here?
- Miss Teschmacher...

242
00:27:36,064 --> 00:27:37,886
...is this a philosophy seminar?

243
00:27:38,047 --> 00:27:39,706
